{{Use British English|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox flag |Name = Saint Kitts and Nevis |Image = Flag of Saint Kitts and Nevis.svg |Nickname = |Use = 111110 |Symbol = |Proportion = 2:3 |Adoption = 19 September 1983 |Design = A yellow-edged black diagonal band bearing two white five-pointed stars divided diagonally from the lower hoist-side corner to the upper fly-side corner: the upper triangle is green and the lower triangle is red. |Designer = Edrice Lewis |Type = National and civil | Image2 = Naval Ensign of Saint Kitts and Nevis.svg | Nickname2 = Naval Ensign of Saint Kitts and Nevis | Use2 = 000001 | Proportion2 = 1:2 | Adoption2 = | Design2 = | Designer2 = }} The '''flag of Saint Kitts and Nevis''' consists of a yellow-edged black band containing two white stars that divides diagonally from the lower hoist-side corner, with a green upper triangle and red lower triangle. Adopted in 1983 to replace the [[flag of Saint Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla]], it has been the [[flag]] of the Federation of [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] since the country gained independence that year. Although the flag utilises the colours of the [[Pan-Africanism|Pan-Africanist]] movement, the symbolism behind them is interpreted differently.<ref>{{cite book|url=|title=Flags|publisher=HarperCollins UK|year=1992|last=Shaw|first=Carol P.|pages=|accessdate=|isbn=0-00-470114-3}}</ref> The three islands later became part of the [[West Indies Federation]] in 1958; after this dissolved four years later, they were granted the status of associate state as [[Saint Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla]].<ref name=EB>{{cite encyclopedia|first=Whitney|last=Smith|encyclopedia=Encyclopædia Britannica|title=Saint Kitts and Nevis, flag of|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1355479/Saint-Kitts-and-Nevis-flag-of|accessdate=June 10, 2013|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.}} '''{{subscription required}}</ref> However, Anguilla decided to secede from the federation in 1969,<ref name=imperialism>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uyqepNdgUWkC&pg=PA28&dq=history+of+st.+kitts+and+nevis#v=onepage&q=history%20of%20st.%20kitts%20and%20nevis&f=false|title=Historical Dictionary of European Imperialism|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|date=January 1, 1991|editor1-first=James Stuart|editor1-last=Olson|editor2-first=Robert|editor2-last=Shadle|pages=28|accessdate=June 10, 2013|isbn=9780313262579}}</ref> owing to fears that their population, which was already small, would be further marginalised in parliament.<ref name=EB/> This was eventually formalised in 1980,<ref name=imperialism/> and a new flag for the remaining parts of the federation was needed, since the symbolism of the previous flag centred on the concept of a union of three.<ref name=EB/>
[[File:Flag of Nevis.svg|thumbnail|left|Flag of [[Nevis]].]]
A national competition was held in the early 1980s to choose a new flag. The winning design by student Edrice Lewis was one of 258 entries.<ref name=complete>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=anBaE-TAlcUC&pg=PA33&dq=Flag+of+St.+Kitts+and+Nevis#v=onepage&q=Flag%20of%20St.%20Kitts%20and%20Nevis&f=false|title=Complete Flags of the World|publisher=Dorling Kindersley Ltd.|date=November 3, 2008|last=Kindersley|first=Dorling|pages=33|accessdate=June 10, 2013|isbn=9781405333023}}</ref> It was first hoisted one minute after midnight on 19 September 1983, the day Saint Kitts and Nevis became an independent country.<ref>{{cite news|title=Newest Caribbean Flag Is Raised Over Tiny State Of St. Kitts–Nevis|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB35D97294A3AE2&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|date=September 20, 1983|accessdate=June 10, 2013|first=Harvey|last=Hagman|page=18A|newspaper=The Miami Herald|agency=Associated Press}} '''{{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=St. Kitts–Nevis: New nation born|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5-FNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SosDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6404,2852361&dq=flag+of+saint+kitts+and+nevis&hl=en|date=September 19, 1983|accessdate=June 10, 2013|first=Dan|last=Sewell|page=4|newspaper=The Free Lance-Star|location=Fredericksburg|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>
==Design== ===Symbolism=== The colours and symbols of the flag carry cultural, political, and regional meanings. The green alludes to the country's fertile land, while the red evokes the fight for freedom against slavery and colonialism. The yellow stripes represent the sunshine the islands enjoy all year round, and the black epitomises the people's African origins.<ref name=EB/><ref name=complete/> The two stars on the black band symbolise [[Saint Kitts|Saint Christopher]] and [[Nevis]]<ref name=EB/><ref name=CIA>{{cite web|title=Saint Kitts and Nevis|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/sc.html|date=|accessdate=June 10, 2013|work=The World Factbook|publisher=CIA}}</ref>—the two islands that make up the federation—as well as "hope and liberty."<ref name=complete/><ref name=CIA/> The official meaning behind the flag's symbols was formulated by Edrice Lewis, the same person who designed the flag.<ref name=complete/>
===In Popular Culture=== The flag of Saint Kitts and Nevis is mentioned in Series 10 Episode 7 of The Big Bang Theory titled "The Veracity Elasticity" in which Sheldon says "......so let's roll up our sleevis and get to know Nevis."
